It's not a problem.

Energy conservation is not a general &quot;law&quot;, it is merely a consequence
of Noether's theorem applied to time translation invariance. In regions
of manifolds which posses a timelike Killing vector[#], one _can_ define
energy in a straightforward way such that it is conserved. In manifolds
that posses no such Killing vector, energy conservation cannot be
expected, and these are the ones in which energy is not well defined.

[#] a timelike Killing vector means that the metric of
the manifold is time translation invariant (i.e. when
one uses the Killing vector as the time axis, the metric
is independent of time).

Note also that GR always has LOCAL energy conservation. This is really
what has been tested so extensively here on earth.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Does this mean GR is false
&gt; as it doesn't take into account the conservation laws?
">

No.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What have physicists come up to solve the problem?
">

There is no problem.

BTW momentum conservation is the same, except it is related to spatial
translation invariance; and angular momentum is related to rotational
invariance.

Tom Roberts
