Dac says...

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;If energy is not well defined and not conserved. Then where
&gt;does it go?
">

Let me illustrate the problem here very simply. Suppose I throw
a ball straight up into the air. The ball has kinetic energy,
but as the ball rises, it *loses* kinetic energy, until it reaches
the top of its trajectory. At that point, it has *zero* kinetic
energy. Where did the energy go?

Well, you could say that it goes into gravitational potential
energy. That answer can be made to work even in General Relativity.
However, &quot;gravitational potential energy&quot; is not a physically
meaningful quantity. It's an artifact of a particular choice
of coordinate system (the fact that you chose a coordinate
system in which the Earth is at rest).

When people say that energy is not conserved in General Relativity,
they mean that there is no coordinate-independent notion of
&quot;the energy of the universe&quot;. If you pick a specific coordinate
system, you can define a conserved quantity that works sort of like
energy but it is not covariant. (That is, it doesn't obey the usual
rules for translating from one coordinate system to another).

--
