In general, for a curved manifold, this fails. Basically one cannot
perform the requisite integrals in a curved manifold. The inability to
define &quot;energy&quot; over a finite region is inherent, and deep.

For certain manifolds one can do what you describe. Specifically, either
the region of the manifold must have a timelike Killing vector, or ALL
energy and momentum must be confined to a compact region of an infinite
manifold with spatial topology R^3 (there might be additional caveats,
but those are the main ones). For the latter case the result is a
conserved _total_ energy, but one cannot in general define individual
energies of sub-regions.

