There are two interpretations to how things should move governed by
the concept of spacetime in general.

1)  Geodesics follow the path of the maximum accumulated spacetime -
This is the most popular model of geodesics.  In this case, all
photons see each path with spacetime of exactly equivalent to zero.
Therefore, light cannot be predicted to move along a certain path.  In
this model, energy is not conserved due to the none-zero result of the
Euler-Lagrange equation associated with the state variable of
spacetime.  The Lagrangian is very simply the following.

L_s = g_ij dq^i/ds dq^j/ds = 1

Where

**  i, j = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
**  dq^0 = c dt
**  ds = segment of spacetime

2)  Geodesics follow the path of the minimum accumulated time - This
is not well accepted because it fails to explain a few of the
predictions ever so well predicted by GR.  In this model, photons can
only move at a specific path that the result would accumulate the
least amount of time in accordance with the Snell's law.  In addition,
this model allows the conservation of energy to be a universally
fundamental property as demanded by the Euler-Lagrange equation
associated with the state variable of time.  The Lagrangian for this
model of geodesic is the following (derived from the above equation)
--- yes a little bit more complicated.

L_t = (ds/dq^0)^2 / g_00 - 2 g_0i dq^u/dq^0 / g_00 - g_uv dq^u/dq^0
dq^v/dq^0 / g_00 = 1

Where

**  u, v = 1, 2, 3
